Bromford Housing Group Limited, (Parent of the Group) as a central purchasing body on behalf of itself and any of its current or future entities and subsidiaries (together "Bromford") wishes to invite interested organisations ("Potential Suppliers") to participate in a procurement process to award a Contract for the reliable Supply of Maintenance and Repair Services of Passenger, Stair and Vertical Platform Lifts.
The Authority is seeking to establish either a contract with a single Supplier with capability and capacity to deliver Maintenance and Repair Services across the entire portfolio of lifts or multiple Suppliers specialising in a particular type(s) of lifting equipment (i.e. passenger, stair or vertical platform lifts). 
To this end the ITT is split into four lots:
Lot 1 - Passenger Lifts, 
Lot 2 - Stair lifts, 
Lot 3 - Vertical Platform Lifts, and
Lot 4 - Passenger Lifts, Stairlifts &amp; Vertical Platform Lifts (combined lot).
A successful Supplier will be required to:
&bull;	Provide an initial condition report in accordance with BS EN 81‐80 and other applicable standards and guidelines;
&bull;	Provide Planned Preventative Maintenance (PPM) and Servicing of passenger, stair and vertical platform lifts and associated infrastructure;
&bull;	Provide reactive repair services, including release of entrapped passengers and fixing all electrical, electronic and mechanical breakdowns, including those caused by a lightning strike or a power cut, and causing partial or total interruption or failure of a lift system; with such services being available on a 24 hrs. 7 days a week basis;
&bull;	Undertake a detailed inspection and testing of the lift systems including the submission of a written report at the request of the Client&#039;s Contract Manager at any time during the Contract;
&bull;	When requested, replace stair lifts and vertical platform lifts that are beyond economical repair; 
&bull;	Address any actions / comments that have arisen out of an insurance inspection by an independent competent person;
&bull;	Provide necessary customer liaison services;
&bull;	Manage and maintain up-to-date asset register; and
&bull;	Collate and report upon usage in order to develop trend management information that allows monitoring contract expenditure and breakdown statistics.
The Supplier shall be responsible for all elements and component parts of the lift installation.
All Services to be provided in accordance with LOLER, PUWER, LEIA Safety Charter, original equipment manufacturer&#039;s guidelines and all other applicable statutory and regulatory requirements and standards.
The assets are spread across multiple locations.

Teignbridge District Council, on behalf of a collaborative group of public bodies across the South West region of the United Kingdom, is undertaking the procurement of a Framework Agreement for the Supply, Installation, Maintenance and Repair of Stairlifts and associated equipment. 

The Framework Agreement will be awarded on the basis of the following Lots:

Lot One (1) The supply, installation and maintenance under warranty of external straight stair lifts including ancillary works;
Lot Two (2) The supply, installation and maintenance under warranty of internal straight stair lifts including ancillary works;
Lot Three (3) The supply, installation and maintenance under warranty of external curved stair lifts including ancillary works;
Lot Four (4) The supply, installation and maintenance under warranty of internal curved stair lifts including ancillary works;
Lot Five (5) The supply, installation and maintenance under warranty of internal and external step lifts including ancillary works;
Lot Six (6) The supply, installation and maintenance under warranty of internal and external platform lifts including ancillary works;
Lot Seven (7) The supply, installation and maintenance under warranty of vertical through-floor lifts including ancillary works;
Lot Eight (8) Recycled Equipment.
Lot Nine (9) The leasing of equipment. 

The Framework Agreement period shall be up to four (4) years from 2016 to 2020. 

Teignbridge District Council is tendering on behalf of itself and the following local authorities:

East Devon District Council
Exeter City Council
Mid Devon District Council
North Devon District Council
Plymouth City Council
South Hams District Council
Teignbridge District Council		
Torridge District Council
West Devon Borough Council.

Leicester City Council&#039;s Adult Social Care Team requires personal lifts and hoists, installation and service and maintenance .  We require:
Lifts 
-	Straight stair lifts 
-	Through floor lifts 
-	Step lifts 
-	External stair lifts 
-	Curved stair lifts 
Hoists  
-	Ceiling track hoists - straights/ curved/ H tracks 
-	Gantry hoists. 
The Supplier will also be expected to:
1.	Joint visits to be provided by the Company to provide quotes for goods such as lifts and hoists;
2.	Where applicable Company to visit on their own to obtain quotes for good such as lifts;
3.	All quotes for goods to be cost effective;
4.	To acknowledge all individual specifications of the goods to be provided to that of the User/s;
5.	Timely provision of goods - hoists and lifts;
6.	Installation and full onsite health and safety checks of the goods provided;
7.	Provision of service and maintenance of lifts and hoists including the Councils existing stock;
8.	To provide a 4-hour response to lift/ hoist breakdowns;
9.	To update and maintain the Councils assets lists;
10.	To provide a means for fast tracking orders and repair where required;
11.	To complete building work as and when required to safely install the lift/ hoist.

The Corporate Officer of the House of Lords and the Corporate Officer of the House of Commons (acting jointly) are inviting expressions of interest from suitably qualified organisations wishing to enter into a contract for the provision of specialist lift consultancy services. The appointed Consultant will support the Authority&#039;s Property and Asset Strategy (PAS) team in its role as custodian of the lift engineering infrastructure on the Parliamentary Estate to review and update technical standards and a long-term strategy for lift modernisation. 

More specifically, the appointed Consultant shall be required to provide specialist services which will include independent advisory support to ensure the viability and quality of lift designs, as well as undertaking other consultancy activities with the view of supporting Parliamentary lift refurbishment projects, which are being delivered in accordance with the RIBA Work Plan 2020. The contract shall be let based on the NEC4 Professional Services Short Contract (NEC4 PSSC).

A non-exhaustive list of the services required to be delivered under the contract are summarised below:
•	Produce lift technical design reviews covering RIBA Stages 2 to 5 inclusive in relation to the Authority&#039;s Lift Refurbishment Programme, as well as work collaboratively with Lift Refurbishment delivery teams and prioritise the works having due regard to Health &amp; Safety and business continuity objectives (as set out within the procurement documents);
•	Review and develop (if needed) existing lift modernisation scope documents;  
•	Produce feasibility studies to RIBA Stage 1 or equivalent, technical standards and engineering specifications;
•	Undertake site inspections and witnessing across the Parliamentary Estate as set out within the procurement documents; 
•	Review lift traffic analysis from previous studies and project consultants and where necessary undertake new traffic analysis and propose optimum lift design strategy for the population and use patterns of the Parliamentary Estate; and
•	Carry out whole of life costing with the view of ensuring that value for money is achieved by taking a holistic approach to design the lifts in relation to each other, traffic flow, building occupants, logistics, fire evacuation strategy, access control and security strategy, environment and sustainability, heritage and conservation and user priorities. 

The procurement documents shall be made available subject to the return of a duly signed Non-Disclosure Agreement (NDA) template, which can be accessed at https://atamis-ukparliament.my.site.com/login
The Authority will aim to execute the signed NDAs and share the tender pack with Tenderers who have submitted a duly signed NDA within two (2) working days of the submission date via the message centre of the Authority&#039;s electronic tendering portal Atamis (please refer to above-mentioned address).

The appointed Consultant will be responsible for the design development and potentially the implementation of both the Port Facilities, comprising Security, Containing Handling, Customs and Immigration and Bio-security, and the planning and potential development of Warehousing development in Rupert’s Valley.

The key requirements relating to the proposed Port Facilities would include:

i.	In consultation with key stakeholders, prepare designs for the appropriate Port Facilities taking into consideration the current Rupert’s Valley Development Plan;
 
ii.	Consideration and reporting on the impacts of the facility on the Environment of Rupert’s Valley, including an Environmental Management Plan;
 
iii.	Assessment of the risks associated with the development and the location, including appropriate levels of acceptance and risk mitigation measures (with costings);

iv.	Further assess the needs of the Island for containerised cargo, including planned growth over a defined period, through stakeholder consultation. This may be used as the basis of providing options to the client and ultimately the detailed design of a fully functional container park to meet these purposes, but it shall at a minimum be capable of accommodating 150 – 200 stuffed Twenty foot containers (TEUs) and 150 – 200 empty TEUs in the best possible configuration to suit an approved logistics and operation plan. Consideration shall be given to the possible complete or partial transition to Forty foot containers in the future;

v.	Logistics management of the facility, including off-loading and reloading operations to minimise the ship at berth time in the wharf and the development of container and goods handling strategy and customs protocols;

vi.	A multipurpose facility to accommodate Customs & Excise, Bio-security, Port Management and Immigration. Whilst the Port Facilities are primarily for the cargo handling, it is likely that immigration services will have to be provided for ships’ crew and also the possibility of landing Cruise Passengers;

vii.	Provide the day-to-day supervisory project management and technical support for the implementation of the approved designs for the Port Facilities;

viii.	The Port Facilities should be designed with the intention of achieving International Ship and Port Security (ISPS) certification.
 
ix.	Integration of 3rd Party works and programme in to the design including becoming a member on the Rupert’s Development working group.

The contract is for the provision, cleaning and maintenance of advertising bus shelters, and operation of advertising on the shelters including:

i. advertising rights on Shelters;

ii. procure and supply Shelter infrastructure;

iii. the provision of all advertising units (Digital Advertising Panels and/or Paper Advertising) as part of Shelters;

iv. oversee the implementation and associated risks with managing the transition from existing to new;

v. install Shelter infrastructure;

vi. associated electrical and connectivity works;

vii. clean, repair and maintain all Shelter infrastructure;

viii. relocation and/or removal of Shelters when instructed by or arranged with the Authority, including (but not limited to) in cases of changes to bus routes; repeated vandalism; or remodelling of the highway as part of wider schemes; and

ix. removal of shelters at the end of the contract if required by the terms of the Contract or agreed with the Authority.

Our current agreement for the provision of bus shelters expires in November 2017 and so the Council is considering our options for the future provision of bus shelters and associated services. As part of this process we are undertaking market engagement prior to 1 or more potential tenders.

We are interested in hearing from organisations who may wish to supply 1, or more, or all of the following:

- Supply and installation of bus shelters;

- Cleaning of bus shelters;

- Maintenance of bus shelters;

- Advertising on bus shelters;

- Other services associated with bus shelters.

Further details are available on our website at: http://www.testvalley.gov.uk/business/doingbusiness/tenders/

Newcastle City Council are currently seeking an organisation to carry out the provision, installation and maintenance of bus shelters across the city. 
This contract includes; 
* Advertising rights on bus shelters only; 
* Supply, installation, repair and maintain advertising shelters; 
* Associated electrical works; 
* Cleaning; and
 * Relocation of shelters as and when required.
